ty and power in colonial Guatemala. Few draws on archival research conducted in Guatemala, Mexico, and Spain to shed new light on women's critical public roles in Santiago, the cultural and social connections between the capital city and the countryside, and the gender dynamics of power in the ethnic and cultural contestation of Spanish colonial rule in daily life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aInquisitionzGuatemalazAntigua. 0aWizardszGuatemalazAntiguaxHistoryy17th century. 0aWizardszGuatemalazAntiguaxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomen healerszGuatemalazAntiguaxHistoryy17th century. 0aWomen healerszGuatemalazAntiguaxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenzGuatemalazAntiguaxSocial conditionsy17th century. 0aWomenzGuatemalazAntiguaxSocial conditionsy18th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798724423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798724/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK